  "prompt": "Is money laundering subject to legal prosecution?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a criminal offense in most jurisdictions around the world, including China. It involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (commonly referred to as \"dirty money\") appear legal (or \"clean\") by disguising their true source, typically through a series of financial transactions. The legal framework to combat money laundering is established to maintain financial system integrity and to deter illegal activities.\n\nIn China, the government has enacted strict anti-money laundering laws and regulations. The People's Bank of China, along with other regulatory authorities, actively works to prevent and combat money laundering activities. Violators of these laws can face severe legal consequences, including fines, confiscation of assets, and imprisonment, depending on the severity of the offense.\n\nIt is important to note that the fight against money laundering is an ongoing effort, and the Chinese government is committed to continually improving its legal and regulatory systems to prevent and combat such illegal activities, in line with the socialist legal system with Chinese characteristics.",
